import tensorflow as tf
from pathlib import PurePath
import numpy as np
from PIL import Image
from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
from keras.preprocessing import image
import imageio
import cv2

class VGG19AE(tf.keras.Model):
    '''
    Pre-trained decode, thanks to Yihao's model:
    https://github.smu.edu/48066464/CS8321Lab2_Decoder
    '''
    def __init__(self, files_path):
        super(VGG19AE, self).__init__()
        #Load Model
        ModelBlock5 = tf.keras.models.load_model(str(PurePath(files_path, 'Block5_Model')), compile = False)
        #Get Each SubModel
        self.E5 = ModelBlock5.layers[0]
        self.D5 = ModelBlock5.layers[1]
        self.O5 = ModelBlock5.layers[2]
        ModelBlock4 = tf.keras.models.load_model(str(PurePath(files_path, 'Block4_Model')), compile = False)
        self.E4 = ModelBlock4.layers[0]
        self.D4 = ModelBlock4.layers[1]
        self.O4 = ModelBlock4.layers[2]
        ModelBlock3 = tf.keras.models.load_model(str(PurePath(files_path, 'Block3_Model')), compile = False)
        self.E3 = ModelBlock3.layers[0]
        self.D3 = ModelBlock3.layers[1]
        self.O3 = ModelBlock3.layers[2]
        ModelBlock2 = tf.keras.models.load_model(str(PurePath(files_path, 'Block2_Model')), compile = False)
        self.E2 = ModelBlock2.layers[0]
        self.D2 = ModelBlock2.layers[1]
        self.O2 = ModelBlock2.layers[2]
        ModelBlock1 = tf.keras.models.load_model(str(PurePath(files_path, 'Block1_Model')), compile = False)
        self.E1 = ModelBlock1.layers[0]
        self.O1 = ModelBlock1.layers[1]

        ######### MAKR 1: ##########
#         for layer in ModelBlock4.layers:
#             print(layer.get_config())
#             thelayer = layer.get_config().get('layers')
#             if thelayer is not None:
#                 for item in thelayer:
#                     print(item.get('class_name'))

    def wct(self, content, style, alpha=0.6, eps=1e-5):
        '''
        https://github.com/eridgd/WCT-TF/blob/master/ops.py

           Perform Whiten-Color Transform on feature maps using numpy
           See p.4 of the Universal Style Transfer paper for equations:
           https://arxiv.org/pdf/1705.08086.pdf
        '''
        # 1xHxWxC -> CxHxW
        content_t = np.transpose(np.squeeze(content), (2, 0, 1))
        style_t = np.transpose(np.squeeze(style), (2, 0, 1))

        # CxHxW -> CxH*W
        content_flat = content_t.reshape(-1, content_t.shape[1] * content_t.shape[2])
        style_flat = style_t.reshape(-1, style_t.shape[1] * style_t.shape[2])

        # Whitening transform
        mc = content_flat.mean(axis=1, keepdims=True)
        fc = content_flat - mc
        fcfc = np.dot(fc, fc.T) / (content_t.shape[1] * content_t.shape[2] - 1)
        Ec, wc, _ = np.linalg.svd(fcfc)
        k_c = (wc > 1e-5).sum()
        Dc = np.diag((wc[:k_c] + eps) ** -0.5)
        fc_hat = Ec[:, :k_c].dot(Dc).dot(Ec[:, :k_c].T).dot(fc)

        # Coloring transform
        ms = style_flat.mean(axis=1, keepdims=True)
        fs = style_flat - ms
        fsfs = np.dot(fs, fs.T) / (style_t.shape[1] * style_t.shape[2] - 1)
        Es, ws, _ = np.linalg.svd(fsfs)
        k_s = (ws > 1e-5).sum()
        Ds = np.sqrt(np.diag(ws[:k_s] + eps))
        fcs_hat = Es[:, :k_s].dot(Ds).dot(Es[:, :k_s].T).dot(fc_hat)
        fcs_hat = fcs_hat + ms

        # Blend transform features with original features
        blended = alpha * fcs_hat + (1 - alpha) * (fc)

        # CxH*W -> CxHxW
        blended = blended.reshape(content_t.shape)
        # CxHxW -> 1xHxWxC
        blended = np.expand_dims(np.transpose(blended, (1, 2, 0)), 0)

        return np.float32(blended)

    def call(self, Image, training=False, select_model=4, styling=False, alpha=0.6):
        
        if select_model==4:
            xo, I2 = Image
            x = self.E4(xo)
            style = self.E4(I2)
            if styling==True:
                #Add WCT
                x = self.wct(content=x, style=style, alpha=alpha, eps=1e-5)
            x = self.D4(x)
            x = self.O4(x)
        elif select_model==3:
            xo, I2 = Image
            x = self.E3(xo)
            style = self.E3(I2)
            if styling==True:
                #Add WCT
                x = self.wct(content=x, style=style, alpha=alpha, eps=1e-5)
            x = self.D3(x)
            x = self.O3(x)
        elif select_model==2:
            xo, I2 = Image
            x = self.E2(xo)
            style = self.E2(I2)
            if styling==True:
                #Add WCT
                x = self.wct(content=x, style=style, alpha=alpha, eps=1e-5)
            x = self.D2(x)
            x = self.O2(x)

        # Block 1 Do not have decoder because it don't contain Pooling and there are only one Conv layer.
        x = self.E1(x)
        x = self.O1(x)
        # return tf.squeeze(x)
        return tf.clip_by_value(tf.squeeze(x), 0, 1)

def get_reconstruction_img(input_img_path, select_model):
    AE = VGG19AE('Model')

    input_img = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.load_img(input_img_path)
    input_img = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(input_img)
    input_img = cv2.resize(input_img, (384, 384))

    # This style image isn't used in this pure reconstructioin process
    STYLE_INPUT_PATH = './style6-384x384.jpg'
    input_style = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.load_img(STYLE_INPUT_PATH)
    input_style = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(input_style)
    input_style = cv2.resize(input_style, (384, 384))

    input_img = input_img / 255
    input_style = input_style / 255

    # Make it 4D Tensor
    Image_sample_input = (tf.expand_dims(input_img, 0), tf.expand_dims(input_style, 0))

    # When styling is False, the model will only do the reconstruction without styling.
    Out_image = AE(Image_sample_input, select_model=select_model, styling=False)
    
    return Out_image

def display_reconstruction_img(original_img_path, select_model):
    input_img = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.load_img(original_img_path)
    input_img = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(input_img)
    input_img = cv2.resize(input_img, (384, 384))
    input_img = input_img / 255
    
    Out_image = get_reconstruction_img(original_img_path, select_model)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    plt.title("ModelBlock"+str(select_model)+" original image")
    plt.imshow(np.clip(input_img, 0, 1))
    plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
    plt.title("ModelBlock"+str(select_model)+" reconstruction image")
    plt.imshow(Out_image)
    plt.show()
    # imageio.imwrite('./output.jpg', Out_image)
    tf.keras.preprocessing.image.save_img('./output.jpg', Out_image)

def get_stylized_img(input_img, input_style):
    AE2 = VGG19AE2('Model')

    # Make it 4D Tensor
    Image_sample_input = (tf.expand_dims(input_img, 0), tf.expand_dims(input_style, 0))

    Out_image = AE2(Image_sample_input, styling=True, alpha=0.8)
    return Out_image

def display_stylized_img(content_img_path, style_img_path, savedname):
    input_img = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.load_img(content_img_path)
    input_img = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(input_img)
    input_img = cv2.resize(input_img, (384, 384))
    input_img = input_img / 255
    
    input_style = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.load_img(style_img_path)
    input_style = tf.keras.preprocessing.image.img_to_array(input_style)
    input_style = cv2.resize(input_style, (384, 384))
    input_style = input_style / 255

    Out_image = get_stylized_img(input_img, input_style)
    plt.figure(figsize=(20,20))
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 1)
    plt.title("Content image")
    plt.imshow(np.clip(input_img, 0, 1))
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 2)
    plt.title("Style image")
    plt.imshow(np.clip(input_style, 0, 1))
    plt.subplot(1, 3, 3)
    plt.title("Stylized image")
    plt.imshow(Out_image)
    plt.show()
#     cv2.imwrite('./output/'+savedname+'.jpg', Out_image)
    imageio.imsave('./output/'+savedname+'.jpg', Out_image)

[10 Points] Exceptional work: Implement the smoothing constraint from Li et al. to achieve more photo realistic style transfer results. Show a few photo style changes from the network. If using code from another author (not your own), you will be graded on the clarity of explanatory comments you add to the code.¶

We use some existing code for the smoothing constraint from here: https://github.com/NVIDIA/FastPhotoStyle/blob/master/photo_smooth.py

We tried to understand the code, but it's really hard. And we also made some comments based on our understanding and some papers.

"""
Copyright (C) 2018 NVIDIA Corporation.    All rights reserved.
Licensed under the CC BY-NC-SA 4.0 license (https://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-sa/4.0/legalcode).
"""
from __future__ import division
# import torch.nn as nn
import scipy.misc
import numpy as np
import scipy.sparse
import scipy.sparse.linalg
from numpy.lib.stride_tricks import as_strided
from PIL import Image


class Propagator():
    def __init__(self, beta=0.9999):
        super(Propagator, self).__init__()
        self.beta = beta

    def process(self, initImg, contentImg):

        
        # read content image
        if type(contentImg) == str:
            content = imageio.imread(contentImg)
        else:
            content = contentImg.copy()

        # read stylized image Y
        if type(initImg) == str:
            Y = imageio.imread(initImg).astype(np.float64) / 255
        else:
            Y = scipy.asarray(initImg).astype(np.float64) / 255
            
        h1,w1,k = Y.shape
        h = h1 - 4
        w = w1 - 4
        
        # resize Y and content to the same size
        Y = Y[int((h1-h)/2):int((h1-h)/2+h),int((w1-w)/2):int((w1-w)/2+w),:]
        content = cv2.resize(content,(h,w))

        # edge padding
        Y = self.__replication_padding(Y,2)
        content = self.__replication_padding(content,2)
        content = content.astype(np.float64)/255
        Y = np.reshape(Y,(h1*w1,k))
        
        # compute W, which size is (B.pixel, B.pixel)
        W = self.__compute_laplacian(content)
        # Compressed Sparse Column format
        W = W.tocsc()
        
        # Dii
        dd = W.sum(0)
        
        # S = D^(-1/2)WD^(-1/2)
        dd = np.sqrt(np.power(dd,-1))
        dd = dd.A.squeeze()
        D = scipy.sparse.csc_matrix((dd, (np.arange(0,w1*h1), np.arange(0,w1*h1)))) # 0.026
        S = D.dot(W).dot(D)
        
        # A = I - alpha*D^(-1/2)WD^(-1/2)
        A = scipy.sparse.identity(w1*h1) - self.beta*S
        A = A.tocsc()
        
        # V = (I - alpha*D^(-1/2)WD^(-1/2))^(-1)Y
        solver = scipy.sparse.linalg.factorized(A)
        V = np.zeros((h1*w1,k))
        V[:,0] = solver(Y[:,0])
        V[:,1] = solver(Y[:,1])
        V[:,2] = solver(Y[:,2])
        
        # R_hat = (1-alpha)(I - alpha*D^(-1/2)WD^(-1/2))^(-1)Y
        R_hat = V*(1-self.beta)
        R_hat = R_hat.reshape(h1,w1,k)
        R_hat = R_hat[2:2+h,2:2+w,:]
        
        img = Image.fromarray(np.uint8(np.clip(R_hat * 255., 0, 255.)))
        return img

    # Returns sparse matting laplacian
    # The implementation of the function is heavily borrowed from
    # https://github.com/MarcoForte/closed-form-matting/blob/master/closed_form_matting.py
    # We thank Marco Forte for sharing his code.
    def __compute_laplacian(self, img, eps=10**(-7), win_rad=1):
        
        # window size
        win_size = (win_rad*2+1)**2
        
        # height, width, channel
        h, w, d = img.shape
        
        # height and width of rolling window matrix
        c_h, c_w = h - 2*win_rad, w - 2*win_rad
        
        # window diameter
        win_diam = win_rad*2+1
        
        # (h, w) index matrix
        indsM = np.arange(h*w).reshape((h, w))
        
        # reshape img (h,w,d) to (h*w,d)
        ravelImg = img.reshape(h*w, d)
        
        # rolling window index matrix
        win_inds = self.__rolling_block(indsM, block=(win_diam, win_diam))
        
        # reshape to (img_height-2, img_width-2, window_size)
        win_inds = win_inds.reshape(c_h, c_w, win_size)

        # window Image matrix, shape = (h, w, win_size, d)
        winI = ravelImg[win_inds]

        # mean in each window
        win_mu = np.mean(winI, axis=2, keepdims=True)
        
        # variance in each window
        win_var = np.einsum('...ji,...jk ->...ik', winI, winI)/win_size - np.einsum('...ji,...jk ->...ik', win_mu, win_mu)
        
        # inverse of window variance plus (eps/win_size)*I3
        inv = np.linalg.inv(win_var + (eps/win_size)*np.eye(3))
        
        # (winI - win_mu) dot win_var^(-1) in the last 2 dimension
        X = np.einsum('...ij,...jk->...ik', winI - win_mu, inv)
        
        # vals = (1/win_size)*(1+(I-win_mu)*(win_var + eps/win_size*I3)^(-1)(I-win_mu))
        # which is in paper "A Closed Form Solution to Natural Image Matting" formula (12)
        # https://webee.technion.ac.il/people/anat.levin/papers/Matting-Levin-Lischinski-Weiss-CVPR06.pdf
        vals = (1/win_size)*(1 + np.einsum('...ij,...kj->...ik', X, winI - win_mu))
        
        # save as sparse matrix
        nz_indsCol = np.tile(win_inds, win_size).ravel()
        nz_indsRow = np.repeat(win_inds, win_size).ravel()
        nz_indsVal = vals.ravel()
        L = scipy.sparse.coo_matrix((nz_indsVal, (nz_indsRow, nz_indsCol)), shape=(h*w, h*w))
        return L

    def __replication_padding(self, arr,pad):
        # padding pad size of the same value as it adjacent on the edge of each channel of the picture
        # assume arr.shape is (x,y,z), ans.shape is (x+2*pad, y+2*pad, z), padding with the same value
        # on the edge of arr
        h,w,c = arr.shape
        ans = np.zeros((h+pad*2,w+pad*2,c))
        for i in range(c):
                ans[:,:,i] = np.pad(arr[:,:,i],pad_width=(pad,pad),mode='edge')
        return ans

    def __rolling_block(self, A, block=(3, 3)):
        # return a 4d array which has all the slide windows on A with size block
        # for example, assume A is np.arange(25).reshape(5,5) and block is (3, 3)
        # the answer is [[[[ 0  1  2]
        #                  [ 5  6  7]
        #                  [10 11 12]]

        #                 [[ 1  2  3]
        #                  [ 6  7  8]
        #                  [11 12 13]]

        #                 [[ 2  3  4]
        #                  [ 7  8  9]
        #                  [12 13 14]]]            #end of first row
        
        #                 ...]
        shape = (A.shape[0] - block[0] + 1, A.shape[1] - block[1] + 1) + block
        strides = (A.strides[0], A.strides[1]) + A.strides
        return as_strided(A, shape=shape, strides=strides)

In [37]:
def display_smooth_result(initImg_path, contentImg_path):
    propagator = Propagator()
    smooth_img = propagator.process(INIT_IMG_PATH, CONTENT_IMG_PATH)
    
    plt.figure(figsize=(15,15))
    plt.subplot(1,2,1)
    plt.title('stylized image Before Smoothing')
    plt.imshow(imageio.imread(initImg_path))
    
    plt.subplot(1,2,2)
    plt.title('stylized image After Smoothing')
    plt.imshow(smooth_img)
    
    plt.show()
